<p><strong>14.6 Bindkey Examples</strong></p>

<p>Here are some examples of keyboard bindings:</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bindkey -d</code></p>

<p>Show all of the default key bindings. The application mode entries are marked with [A].</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bindkey -k k1 select 1</code></p>

<p>Make the â€œF1â€ key switch to window one.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bindkey -t foo stuff barfoo</code></p>

<p>Make â€˜fooâ€™ an abbreviation of the word â€˜barfooâ€™. Timeout is disabled so that users can type slowly.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bindkey "\024" mapdefault</code></p>

<p>This key-binding makes â€˜C-tâ€™ an escape character for key-bindings. If you did the above â€˜stuff barfooâ€™ binding, you can enter the word â€˜fooâ€™ by typing â€˜C-t fooâ€™. If you want to insert a â€˜C-tâ€™ you have to press the key twice (i.e., escape the escape binding).</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bindkey -k F1 command</code></p>

<p>Make the F11 (not F1!) key an alternative screen escape (besides â€˜C-aâ€™).</p>
